  {
   "round": 5,
   "hider_text": "The salt stains on the windowpane are still there, even after the rain. They don’t fade. Just shift—like something breathing behind glass.  \n\nI press my palm against the cold spot near the baseboard. It’s not cold all the way through. The wood warps slightly where the light hits, and the shadow bends like a fold in paper. I notice the way dust sits in",
   "seeker_text": "The first time your finger brushes against a cold metal spoon in a dark kitchen.  \nNot the chill, not the texture. It’s the exact moment—fingertip meeting metal—when your body remembers something it didn’t know it had forgotten: that cold can be precise, like a word spoken in a language you’ve never learned. You don’t flinch. You just stop.",
